          <mj-text mj-class="purple h2">iOS 11's most underrated security feature? A password manager</mj-text>
          <mj-image src="http://imgur.com/5nyuYd5.png"></mj-image>
          <mj-text>Apple's iOS 11 comes with a new feature that could finally make passwords less cumbersome. The iPhone and iPad software comes with a password manager, which lets users access their account details for apps and websites.</mj-text>
          <mj-text>Whenever a login box appears -- including in apps -- a small key-prompt will appear, allowing the user to open their bank of passwords. The password manager is protected by the user's device passcode, or Touch ID if it's enabled, to prevent others from snooping.</mj-text>
          <mj-text>Many users new to iOS 11 will find that their password manager already be populated with login information. That's because passwords that were saved in Safari are now stored in the iOS 11's password manager. The key difference is that the saved passwords now work within apps, too.</mj-text>
          <mj-text>Although the feature is a boon for personal user security, at the time of writing, the password manager feature doesn't allow users to generate passwords, a feature of most other password managers.</mj-text>
          <mj-button mj-class="bg-purple" href="http://www.zdnet.com/article/ios-11-underrated-security-feature-iphone-ipad/">
            Read More
          </mj-button>
